This research statement proposes to measure and mitigate
speaker entanglement, where accent features inadvertently
encode who is speaking in accented automatic speech
recognition (ASR). We argue that entanglement inflates
scores under lenient split for the same speaker and worsens
fairness gaps across accents, and we outline a
parameter-efficient mitigation that combines adversarial
de-speakerization with safe conditioning. The plan is
grounded in established results in accented ASR,
domain-adversarial learning, and parameter-efficient
fine-tuning; it is feasible with public datasets and a
frozen Whisper backbone, and can potentially guide
low-resource data collection.